<DOC><DOCNO> DOE1-25-1081 </DOCNO><TEXT>Economic evaluations are a key component in determining whether or nota proposed commercial development should proceed, and in determiningthe make up of the operation. In addition, economic evaluations are importantin directing research and development activities required to supportthe proposed commercial development. With an economic evaluation, itis possible to determine whether or not a process under development hasthe potential to be economically viable. In addition, it is possibleto determine the major capital and operating cost centers associatedwith the process, and the sensitivity of the potential commercial economicsto these cost centers. Research then can be directed towards those factorsthat hold the most potential for achieving economic viability and awayfrom those factors that have a minor economic effect. This paper illustratesthe use of economic evaluations in determining the viability of a proposedcommercial development and the use of the evaluations in determiningthe direction of research and development activities. 1 fig., 8 tabs.</TEXT></DOC>